# Checkbox Component Documentation

---

## 1. Component Overview

The Checkbox is an interactive selection control that allows users to choose one or more options independently from a set. It is a fundamental form element in the TARMAC Design System, providing clear visual feedback for selected, unselected, and partially selected states.

### What It Is

A checkbox is a small square (or rounded) control that toggles between checked and unchecked states when activated. It can also display an indeterminate (partial) state when used in hierarchical selection patterns.

### Purpose in the System

Checkboxes serve as the primary multi-selection control in TARMAC. They enable users to make independent binary choices across one or more options without affecting other selections in the same group.

### Common Usage Contexts

- **Forms**: Accepting terms, selecting preferences, enabling optional fields
- **Settings panels**: Toggling feature flags, notification preferences, privacy options
- **Filters**: Selecting multiple filter criteria in search or data views
- **Multi-selection lists**: Bulk actions in tables, selecting items for batch operations
- **Permission management**: Granting or revoking granular access rights

---

## 2. Usage Guidelines

### When to Use

Use checkboxes when:

- Users can select **multiple options simultaneously** from a group
- Each option is **independent** of the others
- Users need to **enable or disable** a preference or setting
- A **binary choice** (yes/no, on/off) needs to be made within a form context
- A **"select all"** pattern is needed for a group of items
- Users must explicitly **opt in** to something (e.g., terms and conditions)

### When Not to Use

Do not use checkboxes when:

- **Only one option** should be selected from a group → use **Radio Button**
- The interaction represents an **instant toggle** with immediate effect → use **Toggle Switch**
- The selection is from a **long list of options** → use **Multi-select Dropdown** or **Select**
- The action is **destructive or primary** → use **Button** with confirmation
- You need to represent a **range or scale** → use **Slider**

### Checkbox vs Radio Button vs Toggle Switch

| Criteria              | Checkbox              | Radio Button           | Toggle Switch          |
|-----------------------|-----------------------|------------------------|------------------------|
| Selection type        | Multiple              | Single                 | Binary                 |
| Options independent?  | Yes                   | No (mutually exclusive)| N/A                    |
| Requires submission?  | Typically yes         | Typically yes          | No (immediate effect)  |
| Indeterminate state?  | Yes                   | No                     | No                     |
| Common context        | Forms, filters        | Forms, surveys         | Settings, preferences  |

---

## 3. Component Anatomy

The Checkbox component is composed of the following structural elements:

### 3.1 Checkbox Container

The outer boundary of the checkbox control. Defines the clickable hit area and visual boundary. Available in two styles:

- **Box**: Square container with slightly rounded corners (border-radius: 4px)
- **Rounded**: Fully rounded container (border-radius: 50%)

### 3.2 Checkbox Indicator

The visual element that appears inside the container when the checkbox is in a selected state:

- **Checked**: Displays a checkmark icon
- **Indeterminate/Partial**: Displays a horizontal dash/minus icon

The indicator is hidden when the checkbox is unchecked.

### 3.3 Label

The text element positioned to the right of the checkbox control. It describes the option being selected. The label is interactive — clicking it toggles the checkbox state.

**Requirements:**
- Every checkbox must have an associated label (visible or via `aria-label`)
- Labels should be clear, concise, and action-oriented
- Labels align to the vertical center of the checkbox for single-line text
- Multi-line labels align to the top of the checkbox

### 3.4 Supporting Text / Helper Text (Optional)

Additional descriptive text displayed below the label. Used to provide context, clarification, or instructions about the option.

- Displayed in a smaller, muted font
- Should not exceed two lines
- Not interactive

### 3.5 Error Message (Optional)

Validation feedback displayed when the checkbox is in an error state (e.g., required but unchecked). Typically displayed below the checkbox or checkbox group in an error color (red).

### 3.6 Checkbox Group Label (Optional)

A heading or label for a group of related checkboxes. Implemented using `<fieldset>` and `<legend>` for accessibility. Provides context for the group as a whole.

---

## 4. Variants

### 4.1 Default Checkbox

A standalone checkbox without a label. Used only in constrained layouts (e.g., table row selection). Must include `aria-label` for accessibility.

```jsx
<Checkbox aria-label="Select row" />
```

### 4.2 Checkbox with Label

The standard usage. A checkbox paired with a descriptive text label.

```jsx
<Checkbox label="Enable email notifications" />
```

### 4.3 Checkbox with Description

A checkbox with both a label and supporting helper text for additional context.

```jsx
<Checkbox
  label="Marketing emails"
  helperText="Receive updates about new features and promotions"
/>
```

### 4.4 Checkbox Group

Multiple related checkboxes grouped together under a shared heading. Used for multi-select scenarios.

```jsx
<CheckboxGroup label="Notification preferences">
  <Checkbox label="Email" value="email" />
  <Checkbox label="SMS" value="sms" />
  <Checkbox label="Push notifications" value="push" />
</CheckboxGroup>
```

### 4.5 Checkbox with Helper Text

A checkbox group or individual checkbox with instructional text to guide the user.

```jsx
<CheckboxGroup
  label="Permissions"
  helperText="Select the permissions to grant this user"
>
  <Checkbox label="Read" value="read" />
  <Checkbox label="Write" value="write" />
  <Checkbox label="Admin" value="admin" />
</CheckboxGroup>
```

### 4.6 Checkbox with Error

A checkbox displaying a validation error, typically when a required selection has not been made.

```jsx
<Checkbox
  label="I accept the terms and conditions"
  error="You must accept the terms to continue"
  required
/>
```

### 4.7 Indeterminate Checkbox

A checkbox in the partial/indeterminate state. Used as a parent control when only some child checkboxes in a group are selected.

```jsx
<Checkbox
  label="Select all"
  indeterminate={someSelected && !allSelected}
  checked={allSelected}
/>
```

### Color Variants

The TARMAC Design System supports four color variants that define the fill color when checked:

| Variant            | Color   | Usage                                                    |
|--------------------|---------|----------------------------------------------------------|
| **Standard (Black)** | #000000 | Default for most interfaces                              |
| **Blue**           | #2563eb | Interfaces with a blue primary action theme              |
| **Green**          | #16a34a | Positive selections or confirmations                     |
| **DLV Red**        | #dc2626 | Brand-related interfaces or strong visual emphasis        |

Use variants consistently across the product. Do not mix variants within the same form or group.

---

## 5. States

### 5.1 Default (Unchecked)

- **Visual**: Empty container with a visible border
- **Border color**: neutral-300 (#d4d4d4)
- **Background**: Transparent
- **Interaction**: Ready for user input
- **Accessibility**: Announced as "not checked"

### 5.2 Hover

- **Visual**: Border color darkens; subtle background tint may appear
- **Border color**: neutral-400 (#a3a3a3)
- **Cursor**: Pointer
- **Transition**: 150ms ease-in-out
- **Accessibility**: No change in announced state

### 5.3 Focus

- **Visual**: 2px focus ring appears around the checkbox
- **Focus ring color**: Matches variant color (e.g., #000000 for Standard)
- **Outline offset**: 2px
- **Trigger**: Keyboard navigation only (`:focus-visible`)
- **Accessibility**: Focus must be clearly visible; meets 3:1 contrast ratio

### 5.4 Checked

- **Visual**: Container fills with variant color; white checkmark icon appears
- **Background**: Variant color (e.g., #000000 for Standard)
- **Border**: Matches background color
- **Indicator**: White checkmark
- **Accessibility**: Announced as "checked"

### 5.5 Unchecked

- **Visual**: Same as Default state
- **Accessibility**: Announced as "not checked"

### 5.6 Indeterminate (Partial)

- **Visual**: Container fills with variant color; horizontal dash icon appears
- **Background**: Variant color
- **Indicator**: White horizontal line (minus icon)
- **Usage**: Parent checkbox when some but not all children are selected
- **Accessibility**: Announced as "partially checked" via `aria-checked="mixed"`

### 5.7 Disabled

- **Visual**: Reduced opacity (40%); muted colors
- **Background**: neutral-50 (#f5f5f5) or transparent
- **Border**: neutral-200 (#e5e5e5)
- **Cursor**: not-allowed
- **Interaction**: No hover, focus, or click response
- **Tab order**: Removed from keyboard navigation
- **Accessibility**: Announced as "dimmed" or "unavailable"
- **Note**: Can appear in both checked and unchecked states

### 5.8 Error

- **Visual**: Border color changes to error-600 (#dc2626); error message appears below
- **Error text**: error-700 (#991b1b)
- **Interaction**: Fully interactive; error clears on valid input
- **Accessibility**: Error message linked via `aria-describedby`

### 5.9 Active / Pressed

- **Visual**: Slightly darker than hover state; brief depression effect
- **Duration**: Momentary (during click/tap)
- **Transition**: 100ms
- **Accessibility**: No change in announced state

---

## 6. Sizes

The TARMAC Design System supports three checkbox sizes:

### 6.1 Small

| Property           | Value    |
|--------------------|----------|
| Checkbox dimension | 16 × 16px |
| Icon size          | 10px     |
| Label font size    | 14px     |
| Label line height  | 20px     |
| Control-to-label gap | 8px   |
| Min touch target   | 44 × 44px |

**Usage**: Dense environments such as data tables, compact lists, and toolbars.

### 6.2 Medium (Default)

| Property           | Value    |
|--------------------|----------|
| Checkbox dimension | 20 × 20px |
| Icon size          | 12px     |
| Label font size    | 16px     |
| Label line height  | 24px     |
| Control-to-label gap | 8px   |
| Min touch target   | 44 × 44px |

**Usage**: Standard forms, settings panels, and most interface contexts.

### 6.3 Large

| Property           | Value    |
|--------------------|----------|
| Checkbox dimension | 24 × 24px |
| Icon size          | 14px     |
| Label font size    | 18px     |
| Label line height  | 28px     |
| Control-to-label gap | 8px   |
| Min touch target   | 44 × 44px |

**Usage**: Spacious layouts, onboarding flows, and high-emphasis forms.

**Important**: Regardless of visual size, the interactive touch target must remain at least 44 × 44px to meet accessibility requirements.

---

## 7. Interaction Behavior

### 7.1 Toggle Behavior

- Clicking the checkbox control toggles between checked and unchecked states
- Clicking the label text also toggles the checkbox
- Each click cycles: unchecked → checked → unchecked
- Indeterminate state is only set programmatically, never by user click

### 7.2 Multi-Select Behavior

- Multiple checkboxes in a group can be selected independently
- Selecting one checkbox does not affect the state of others in the group
- No minimum or maximum selection is enforced by default (configurable via validation)

### 7.3 Indeterminate / Partial Behavior

- Used in parent-child checkbox hierarchies
- When **all children** are checked → parent shows **checked**
- When **some children** are checked → parent shows **indeterminate**
- When **no children** are checked → parent shows **unchecked**
- Clicking an indeterminate parent checkbox **checks all children**
- Clicking a checked parent checkbox **unchecks all children**

### 7.4 Validation Behavior

- Validation runs on form submission by default
- Can be configured to validate on blur or on change
- Required checkboxes show error state when unchecked on submission
- Error message appears below the checkbox or group
- Error state clears when the user checks the required checkbox

### 7.5 Group Behavior

- Checkbox groups should be wrapped in a `<fieldset>` with a `<legend>`
- Group-level validation can enforce minimum/maximum selections
- "Select all" checkbox at the top of a group controls all children
- Group state updates propagate to the parent "select all" checkbox

### 7.6 Disabled Behavior

- Disabled checkboxes cannot be toggled by click, tap, or keyboard
- Disabled checkboxes are removed from the tab order
- Disabled state can apply to individual checkboxes or an entire group
- Visual opacity is reduced to 40%

---

## 8. Accessibility

### 8.1 Keyboard Interactions

| Key             | Action                                      |
|-----------------|---------------------------------------------|
| `Tab`           | Move focus to the next focusable checkbox    |
| `Shift + Tab`   | Move focus to the previous focusable checkbox|
| `Space`         | Toggle the focused checkbox (check/uncheck)  |

- Disabled checkboxes are skipped in the tab order
- Focus order follows the visual DOM order
- No keyboard traps

### 8.2 Screen Reader Behavior

- Each checkbox must be associated with a visible label or `aria-label`
- Screen readers announce: role ("checkbox"), label text, and current state
- State announcements:
  - Unchecked: "not checked"
  - Checked: "checked"
  - Indeterminate: "partially checked" or "mixed"
  - Disabled: "dimmed" or "unavailable"
- Checkbox groups should use `<fieldset>` and `<legend>` so screen readers announce the group context

### 8.3 ARIA Attributes

| Attribute           | Usage                                                        |
|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|
| `role="checkbox"`   | Implicit when using `<input type="checkbox">`. Required for custom implementations. |
| `aria-checked`      | `"true"`, `"false"`, or `"mixed"` (for indeterminate)        |
| `aria-disabled`     | `"true"` when the checkbox is disabled                       |
| `aria-labelledby`   | References the ID of the label element                       |
| `aria-describedby`  | References the ID of helper text or error message            |
| `aria-required`     | `"true"` when the checkbox is required                       |
| `aria-invalid`      | `"true"` when the checkbox is in an error state              |

### 8.4 Focus Visibility

- Focus ring must be visible on keyboard navigation
- Focus ring uses `:focus-visible` (not `:focus`) to avoid showing on mouse click
- Focus ring: 2px solid outline with 2px offset
- Focus ring contrast ratio: ≥ 3:1 against surrounding background
- Focus ring color matches the active variant color

### 8.5 Color and Contrast

- Checkbox border contrast against background: ≥ 3:1
- Checkmark indicator contrast against filled background: ≥ 4.5:1
- Label text contrast: ≥ 4.5:1 (normal text) or ≥ 3:1 (large text)
- Do not rely on color alone to convey state — the checkmark icon provides a shape cue

---

## 9. Layout and Spacing

### 9.1 Spacing Tokens

| Spacing Rule                        | Value   | Token                          |
|-------------------------------------|---------|--------------------------------|
| Checkbox to label                   | 8px     | `--checkbox-label-gap`         |
| Vertical spacing between checkboxes | 8px     | `--checkbox-item-spacing`      |
| Checkbox group spacing (between groups) | 16px | `--checkbox-group-spacing`     |
| Group label to first checkbox       | 8px     | `--checkbox-group-label-gap`   |
| Helper text to checkbox             | 4px     | `--checkbox-helper-gap`        |
| Error message to checkbox           | 4px     | `--checkbox-error-gap`         |

### 9.2 Alignment Rules

- Checkbox control aligns to the **top** of the first line of label text for multi-line labels
- Checkbox control aligns to the **vertical center** of single-line labels
- Labels are always positioned to the **right** of the checkbox (in LTR layouts)
- In RTL layouts, labels appear to the **left** of the checkbox
- Checkbox groups align to the left edge of their container
- Indentation for nested/child checkboxes: 24px from parent

### 9.3 Responsive Behavior

- Checkboxes maintain their size across breakpoints
- Label text may wrap to multiple lines on narrow viewports
- Touch targets remain 44 × 44px minimum on all devices
- Checkbox groups stack vertically on mobile; may use columns on wider viewports

---

